>    A couple of comments:
>
>  ----- liked the dual focus on growth and fairness
> ------also liked the dedication to raising incomes. If that happens,
> everything else is secondary
> -----the main points she made on quarterly capitalism and Wall Street were
> directionally right
> -----think the campaign can do better in explaining the problem with short
> term ism and
>         why it isn't serving the country.   How the focus of our
> capitalism has shifted towards
>          finance, and not for the better. To me, this part of the speech
> wasn't clear or effective
> ----- beyond the good focus on pre-K, I wondered why there wasn't some
> additional
>         focus on raising education outcomes and the ever sharpening
>  linkages between level of
>          education and lifetime earnings; I know that some progressives
> say that focusing on
>         education is a cop- out and that redistribution is the greater
> imperative. But, anyone
>          familiar with David Autor's work knows that this is incorrect
> just in terms of arithmetic.
>         In other words, no amount of redistribution can match the income
> effects of
>          getting more Americans successfully into and out of college
> -----finally, didn't think this was an especially optimistic speech; how
> America has overcome giant obstacles, just in recovering from 2008 ( let
> alone throughout our history)--- only advanced country in the world which
> has done that----and we just need to get our growth engine firing on all
> cylinders now and in a fairer way. But, maybe this is for the general, and
> not now
> ----- also wondered why she didn't stress her experience as two term
> Senator and part of The
>      Clinton years; that  she actually knows a lot about the U.S. economy
> ( must be a good reason for excluding this)
>    ---- comments like these prove that I am no political operative
